6","1096":"1096","1040":"1040","1073":"1073","1050":"1050","1092":"1092","1158":"1158","1069":"1069","Cuinchy, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Cuinchy, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Francie","Europe":"Europe","Daventry, Northamptonshire, England":"Daventry, Northamptonshire, Anglie","Long Buckby, Northamptonshire, England":"Long Buckby, Northamptonshire, Anglie"},"da":{"1066–1098":"1066–1098","1069–1120":"1069–1120","1073–Female":"1073–Afdød","1090–1158":"1090–1158","1092–Female":"1092–Afdød","1040–Male":"1040–Afdød","1050–1131":"1050–1131","1090":"1090","about 1092":"omkring 1092","1066":"1066","1098":"1098","1131":"1131","1120":"1120","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","1040":"1040","1073":"1073","1050":"1050","1092":"1092","1158":"1158","1069":"1069","Cuinchy, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Cuinchy, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Frankrig","Europe":"Europe","Daventry, Northamptonshire, England":"Daventry, Northamptonshire, England","Long Buckby, Northamptonshire, England":"Long Buckby, Northamptonshire, England"},"nl":{"1066–1098":"1066–1098","1069–1120":"1069–1120","1073–Female":"1073–Overleden","1090–1158":"1090–1158","1092–Female":"1092–Overleden","1040–Male":"1040–Overleden","1050–1131":"1050–1131","1090":"1090","about 1092":"circa 1092","1066":"1066","1098":"1098","1131":"1131","1120":"1120","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","1040":"1040","1073":"1073","1050":"1050","1092":"1092","1158":"1158","1069":"1069","Cuinchy, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Cuinchy, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Frankrijk","Europe":"Europa","Daventry, Northamptonshire, England":"Daventry, Northamptonshire, England","Long Buckby, Northamptonshire, England":"Long Buckby, Northamptonshire, England"},"en":{"1066–1098":"1066–1098","1069–1120":"1069–1120","1073–Female":"1073–Deceased","1090–1158":"1090–1158","1092–Female":"1092–Deceased","1040–Male":"1040–Deceased","1050–1131":"1050–1131","1090":"1090","about 1092":"about 1092","1066":"1066","1098":"1098","1131":"1131","1120":"1120","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","1040":"1040","1073":"1073","1050":"1050","1092":"1092","1158":"1158","1069":"1069","Cuinchy, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Cuinchy, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France","Europe":"Europe","Daventry, Northamptonshire, England":"Daventry, Northamptonshire, England","Long Buckby, Northamptonshire, England":"Long Buckby, Northamptonshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Quincy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from any of several places in France deriving their names from the Gallo-Roman personal name <i>Quintus</i>, meaning ‘fifth(-born)’ + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>. The earliest bearer of the name in England, that of Saer de <i>Quincy</i>, ancestor of the earls of Winchester, was from Cuinchy in Pas-de-Calais, but the name may have been reinforced by immigrants from Quincy-sous-Sénard in Seine-et-Oise or Quincy-Voisins in Seine-et-Marne. A family of the name <i>de Quincy</i> held the title Earl of Winchester 1207–65. Descendants of this family later bore the name <i>Quincey</i> up to the time of the English essayist Thomas <i>De Quincey</i> (1785–1859), who changed his name from <i>Quincey</i> to <i>De Quincey</i> in 1796.","History: The American Quincy family were established in MA by Edmund Quincy in 1633. Fifth in descent was Josiah Quincy (1744–75), a leading patriot, who was sent to England to argue the colonists’ case in 1774. His son Josiah (1772–1864) was a powerful opponent of slavery, president of Harvard, and mayor of Boston, a post also held by several of his descendants. The traditional pronunciation is “Quinzy”."],"variants":[{"name":"Quincey","meanings":["English: variant of   Quincy  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":0,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705183,"age":20,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":30,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard de Quincy was born in 1066, in Cuinchy, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France, his father, Robert de Quincy, was 26 and his mother, Matilda, was 17. He married Judith Orabilis. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1098, in Long Buckby, Northamptonshire, England, at the age of 32."},"et":{"1066–1098":"1066–1098","1069–1120":"1069–1120","1073–Female":"1073–Surnud","1090–1158":"1090–1158","1092–Female":"1092–Surnud","1040–Male":"1040–Surn